                        <p>Upon Perdue’s retirement from her field, North Carolina politics made a drastic shift to the right. For the first time in decades, the governor, lieutenant governor and state legislature are solidly Republican. In her time in academia, however, Perdue said she will not be loudly vocal in her opposition of some of the new state government’s policies to abide by what she called a “golden rule” of politics—that an outgoing politician remain relatively quiet in criticism of the incoming politician.</p>
<p>“I do not want to bring partisan politics to Duke,” she said.</p>
<p>After getting her taste of the Duke community in Dodge’s class, Perdue said she is very excited about her fellowship.</p>
<p>“Your generation can change the world,” Perdue said. “That’s why I’m at Duke—that’s why I want to come next Fall.”</p>

